OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Burns Branch is typical of small order streams draining this portion of the parkway.  This site is located adjacent to the parking lot and picnic grounds.  A horse riding trail parallels this stream for some distance upstream.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Cypress Creek, also a popular recreational site, is a broad gravel-bedded stream that parallels the parkway for several kilometers.  This sampling site is at the picnic grounds and public access point 50m from the parking lot.    While the sampling site for Cypress Creek is within the state of Tennessee, it is important to note that the state of Alabama, downstream from the site, considers Cypress Creek an outstanding water (listed in the National Rivers Inventory).  The state considers this water a 'Significant recreational site', and is a 'Designated canoe trail'.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Fall Hollow, similar to Jackson Falls, generally originates from within the parkway corridor.  The site is accessed via a nature trail leading from the parking lot.  Caution should be used during wet and icy conditions.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Glenrock Branch is a popular recreational site for park visitors.  Gravel riffles typify the stream as it flows past limestone outcrops.  The majority of its watershed is within the parkway, with the remaining portion in forested land. Access is gained from the adjacent parking lot.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Jacks Branch is typical of a moderate rock and gravel bedded stream - a modest gradient with frequent riffles and pools.  Access is gained via a path from the adjacent parking lot.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Jackson Falls drains a portion of Jackson Branch largely originating within the parkway corridor.  Access is gained via a nature trail and should be safe in all conditions (the sampler should exercise caution during times of ice and snow).
HorizontalCollectionMethodName: GPS Code (Pseudo Range) Standard Position (SA Off)

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Little Swan Creek at Monument Road
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Little Swan Creek flows along a picnic grounds near at a public access point.  Again, typical of moderate-gradient riffle-pool streams of the northern section of the Trace.  Access is easy and safe in all conditions.
HorizontalCollectionMethodName: GPS Code (Pseudo Range) Standard Position (SA Off)

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The upper Buffalo River can be sampled at the public access point at Metal Ford.  This is the largest public-accessible stream along the Trace.  This site, which is highly visited by recreationalists, is easily sampled in all conditions.  This site may also be known as Steel Branch at Metal Ford.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Sweetwater Branch drains private forested lands west of the parkway.  Similar throughout the region, this gravel-bedded stream flows through riffles and pools.  Access is gained via the adjacent parking lot.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division

Public access is gained by a canoe launch along the Stones River Greenway.  West Fork Stones River itself is listed by the State of Tennessee as a 303d water.  Access is easy and safe in all conditions.  This location is used by the recent USGS water quality inventory.

Access is easy and safe in all conditions.  This location is used by the recent USGS water quality inventory.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 1 - Downstream of Norris Dam: Samples are taken from the Clinch River from the bank at the first recreation access point downstream of Norris Dam.  This site is upstream of any possible DOE impacts and is a reference site in this respect. It may, however, show effects of any agricultural, industrial and residential activities upstream.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 10 - McCoy Branch: Samples are taken from the creek approximately 150-200 feet upstream of the confluence with Melton Hill Lake.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 12 - East Fork of Walker Branch: Samples are taken from the creek in a length of the stream about 150 feet in distance, beginning about 100 feet from the confluence with Melton Hill Lake. The exact location depends upon the water level of the Clinch River at the time of sampling. The gradient of the stream at this point is slight and sometimes the river backs up into the stream, therefore sampling must be done farther upstream to obtain a sample representative of the stream and not the river.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 13 - Bearden Creek: Samples are taken from the creek at point about 150 feet from the confluence with Melton Hill Lake.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 2 - Anderson County Water Treatment Plant: Samples are taken from the Clinch River from a boat in an area approximately 20 to 40 feet from the west bank of the river. This site is upstream of any possible DOE impacts and is a reference site in this respect. It may, however, show effects of any agricultural, industrial and residential activities upstream.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 20 - Grassy Creek: Samples are taken from the stream at a point about one half mile from the confluence with the Clinch River.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 22 - Unnamed Stream: Samples are taken from the stream at the opening of the culvert that brings water from the K-1515C lagoon, approximately 100 feet from the confluence with the Clinch River.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 3 - Melton Hill Park: Samples are taken by the same methods as used at Site 2 in an area approximately 20 to 40 feet from the west bank of the river approximately one half mile downstream of the Knoxville Utility Board's pumping station.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 4 - Grubb Islands: Samples are taken by the same methods as used at Site 2 in an area approximately 20 to 40 feet from the west bank of the river approximately 100 to 200 feet downstream of the larger Grubb Island. The coordinates are approximately 35? 53.917' N latitude and 84? 22.454' W longitude.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 5 - Brashear Island: Samples are taken by the same methods as used at Site 2 in an area approximately 20 to 40 feet south of the last sandbar (going downstream) of the river approximately 400 to 500 feet upstream of Brashear Island.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 6 - Bull Run Steam Plant: Samples are taken by the same methods as used at Site 2 in an area approximately 20 to 40 feet of the west bank of the river at a point near the upstream end of the skimmer wall.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 7 - Water Treatment Plant: Samples are taken by the same methods as used at Site 2 in an area approximately one half mile downstream of the Water Treatment Plant Intake.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 8 - Scarboro Creek: Samples are taken from the creek at a point near the confluence with Melton Hill Lake.

OrganizationFormalName: Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Site 9 - Kerr Hollow Branch: Samples are taken from the creek at a point about 50 feet from the confluence with Melton Hill Lake.
